Linux x86 Assembly: Hello world using NASM

We stand on the shoulders of giants. In this article we pay homage to the forgotten one by learning the basics.

A computer can only understand in 1’s and 0’s. Every instruction or code that we write needs to be converted to byte code for computer to perform operation. We human beings are not good with remembering digits. To make our life bit easier we have created mnemonics for binary code called assembly language.

usage

Nowadays assembly has significantly reduces compared to 15–20 years back. But it is still used in lot of projects like:

  • reverse engineering
  • extreme optimization
  • bios
  • embedded system.

Advantages

Being so close to hardware, there are a lot of advantages to assembly:

  • Assembly has the fastest execution time.
  • It takes the least amount of memory.
  • It makes calls to hardware resources easier.

Disadvantages

For normal day to day programming. C is heavily preferred over assembly for following reasons.

  • Assembly is not scalable. The number of lines in asm increases exponentially for each command we want to run.
  • It will only work with one architecture. For different hardware and OS, we require completely different assembly.
  • It has more memory leaks than C, cause even the stack frames need to be handled by programmer.

Installation

We will be using Netwide Assembler (NASM) for this course. To install the NASM just run the following command.

$ sudo apt install nasm

Introduction

Let me roll over from C as it is the closest things to lower level language that most of us are familiar with.

$ cc -o hello-1 hello-1.c 
$./hello-1
Hello World

This is the program we are all familiar with. Lets use strace to see the communication between process and Linux kernel.

$ strace ./hello-1
...
brk(0x5643c8fd4000) = 0x5643c8fd4000
write(1, “Hello World\n”, 12Hello World
) = 12
exit_group(0) = ?
+++ exited with 0 +++

There are lot of information. But the only one we are concerned is with write. Its syntax is ssize_t write(int fd, const void *buf, size_t count); We are writing count number of bytes starting from from buf to file descriptor fd. The 1 in file descriptor signifies standard output. Lets see if we can go one step closer using the write function instead of printf.

_start is the the entry point to the program from OS prospective while main is the entry point of program from programmers prospective.

$ cc hello.c -nostartfiles

Hello World in Assembly

This is the closest to assembly we are going to get from c. Lets do the same function in assembly.

  • The extension can be *.s, *.S, *.a, or *.asm.
  • Variables are declared under section .data
  • The code is declared under section .text.
  • The function is selection done using rax.
  • First argument is done using rdi.
  • Second argument is rsi.
  • syscall is used to invoke the functionality. Before invoking we should setup the function and variables.

Add the following commands to Makefile:

now execute following instructions.

$ make 
$ ./hello_world
hello_world

Exporting assembly to C

To export the assembly code we just expose the label to outside.

  • Instead of using _start we can use any other name in this case we are using hello_world .
  • Remove exit command.

In the c code we will just define pre-processor and link it during compilation.

To compile We will use:

$nasm -f elf64 -o hello_world.o hello_world.s
$ cc hello.c hello_world.o

Calling C libraries

Writing our 4 lines for printing every time is time consuming and prone to error. Luckily, we can import c libraries in assembly. We can use the popular printf without issue. The c libraries are initialized in _start. So if we want the code to compile with gcc we have to make the label to main.

$ nasm -felf64 hello_world.s 
$ gcc -o hello_world  hello_world.o
$./hello_world

Comparing object files of C and assembly.

The size of the executable is 20kb while the size of executable using assembly is 12 kb. Lets check the contents of assembly object. Using the objdump -D ./hello_world

If you look closely you can see that command destination, source from our code has been inverted to command source, destination. Thats because the object dump uses GAS syntax which is different from what we are using. Now lets compare the same for the executable in c.

We get a lot larger than we were expecting. Why is c files larger than asm? Because C, being a comparatively higher level language adds a lot of boiler plate code added by compiler to help programmers. This does mean a well created assembly will be faster than C.
